const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Why is LA water so bad for commercial steamers?",
    a: "LADWP municipal water runs 8-15 grains per gallon hardness, which is moderate-to-high. In a commercial steamer running through service hours (8-14 hours daily for restaurants and institutional kitchens), the water is continuously evaporated to generate steam, leaving dissolved minerals behind to precipitate as scale on every interior surface: heating elements, water-level probes, water inlet valve internals, the steam generator vessel itself. Untreated LA water can deposit visible scale on a new commercial steamer within 2-3 months. Over a year without descale or softening, scale buildup becomes the dominant failure cause across the entire steamer service category.",
  },
  {
    q: "How often does my steamer need descaling?",
    a: "Depends on your water and your duty cycle. With a properly-sized water softener at the steamer inlet, descale interval extends to 12-18 months on most commercial units. Without a softener, in LADWP territory at 8-12 hours daily duty, every 2-3 months. Heavy duty (institutional cafeterias 12-14 hours daily): every 1-2 months without softener. Cleveland Range and Groen both publish descale schedules in their service manuals; we follow the manufacturer's recommendation calibrated to your actual water hardness and duty cycle. Quarterly is the sweet spot for most LA institutional customers operating without softeners.",
  },
  {
    q: "What does descaling actually involve?",
    a: "Three steps. (1) Drain the steam generator water charge. (2) Fill with descaling solution (manufacturer-specified citric or phosphoric acid blend), heat per the manufacturer's procedure (typically 1-2 hours at low temperature with the boiler isolated from cooking), drain. (3) Rinse cycles (typically 2-3 fresh-water fills + drains) until the rinse water tests neutral. While the system is open, we inspect water-level probes, heating element condition, and inlet valve for residual scale. Total time on-site 90-180 minutes for most commercial steamers. Cost $360-540 typical for descale alone; combined with probe cleaning + inlet inspection often $560-820.",
  },
  {
    q: "Should I install a water softener?",
    a: "For high-duty institutional kitchens (LAUSD cafeterias, hospital food service, hotel banquet kitchens running 12+ hours daily), yes. The math is straightforward: a $1,200-2,500 plumbing-trade water softener install at the steamer inlet line plus annual salt and resin maintenance ($200-400/year) prevents $1,500-3,000 of descale + heating element + probe replacement work over 3-5 years. For low-duty operations (restaurant kitchens running 4-6 hours daily on the steamer), the math is less clear and quarterly descale alone may be the right choice. We do the consultation, refer to plumbing partners for the softener install, and don't pressure either way.",
