<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · LA water and commercial steamers</p>
    <h2>The math behind quarterly descale.</h2>

    <p>LADWP municipal water (the dominant supply across LA County, with portions of OC, Ventura, San Bernardino, and Riverside on different supply systems with similar or higher hardness) tests 8-15 grains per gallon hardness depending on the source mix and time of year. This is moderate-to-high hardness territory. Most domestic appliances accommodate this water without issue because daily duty cycles are short and water exposure is intermittent. Commercial steamers don't have that luxury: they run 8-14 hours daily, continuously evaporating water and concentrating dissolved minerals into precipitating scale on every interior surface.</p>

    <p>Without intervention, an untreated commercial steamer in LADWP territory will accumulate visible scale within 2-3 months of new installation, develop measurable performance degradation within 6-9 months, and start showing component failures (water-level probe misreads, water inlet restrictions, heating element insulation failures) within 12-18 months. By year 3, an untreated steamer typically has had multiple emergency service calls and is approaching premature replacement.</p>

    <p>The economics favor prevention. A scheduled quarterly descale at $400-500 per visit is much cheaper than emergency element + probe + inlet valve replacement at $1,500-2,500 when scale buildup precipitates a multi-component failure. Combined with a $1,200-2,500 water softener install (one-time plumbing-trade scope, plus annual salt/resin maintenance at $200-400/year), descale interval extends to 12-18 months and emergency calls drop near zero on the steam equipment side.</p>

    <p>$120 commercial diagnostic, applied to descale and repair work. Same-day across LA, OC, Ventura. Phones answered 24/7. BHGS #A49573, EPA 608 Universal certified #1346255700410. Parent: <a href="/commercial/steamer-repair/">commercial steamer repair</a>.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · How scale damages commercial steamers</p>
    <h2>Five failure pathways from a single underlying cause.</h2>

    <h3 class="cause-h3">1. Heating element insulation and eventual failure</h3>
    <p>Mineral scale precipitates onto the heating element surface as a hard white-to-grey crust. The crust acts as thermal insulation, requiring the element to run hotter to transfer the same heat to the surrounding water. Over months to a year, elevated element temperature accelerates element wire degradation, eventually causing open-circuit failure. Replacement runs $640-920 typical. Scale-driven element failures are the highest-cost scale-related repair we see.</p>

    <h3 class="cause-h3">2. Water-level probe insulation</h3>
    <p>Water-level probes use electrical conductivity through the water to detect water level. Scale coating insulates the probe surface, the controller misreads water level, and either the steamer won't fill (false 'tank full') or floods the chamber (false 'tank empty'). Probe cleaning runs $200-280; replacement when scale damage is irreversible $260-440.</p>

    <h3 class="cause-h3">3. Water inlet valve restriction</h3>
    <p>The water inlet valve sees a continuous concentration gradient at the valve seat as water enters the steam generator. Scale precipitates at the valve seat over time, restricting flow. Symptom: steamer fills slowly. Cleaning/replacement $260-440.</p>

    <h3 class="cause-h3">4. Steam generator vessel scale layer</h3>
    <p>Scale builds up on every interior surface of the steam generator vessel. Heavy buildup reduces vessel volume (less water capacity = less steam capacity), can flake into the steam supply line (carrying scale particles into the cooking chamber), and provides nucleation sites for accelerated future scaling. Descale runs $360-540.</p>

    <h3 class="cause-h3">5. Drain valve seat scale</h3>
    <p>The drain valve seat accumulates scale similarly to the inlet valve. Symptom: drain incomplete after operator-initiated drain cycle, residual water in vessel after shutdown. Cleaning runs $200-340 typically as part of full descale service.</p>
  </div>
</section>

